05345nam a22008175i 9780231544030DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018056847  a97802315440307 a10.7312/lemb182162doi  a(DE-B1597)526838  a(OCoLC)1118692187  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aP96.I5bL46 2019 7aBUS0700602bisacsh04a302.2309/0452231 aLemberg, Diana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBarriers Down :bHow American Power and Free-Flow Policies Shaped Global Media /cDiana Lemberg. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b15 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. LIBERALIZING MISSIONS -- t1. Freedom for Every Medium, Everywhere -- t2. Quantifying and Qualifying Freedom of Information During the Early Cold War -- t3. Information Flows and the Conundrum of Multilingualism -- t4. Capacity as Freedom During the Development Decade -- t5. Satellites and the End of Sovereignty -- t6. Cultural Turns in the International Arena -- t7. “A Global First Amendment War” -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFreedom of information is a principle commonly associated with the United States’ First Amendment traditions or digital-era technology boosters. Barriers Down reveals its unexpected origins in political, economic, and cultural battles over analog media in the postwar period. Diana Lemberg traces how the United States shaped media around the world after 1945 under the banner of the “free flow of information,” showing how the push for global media access acted as a vehicle for American power.Barriers Down considers debates over civil liberties and censorship in Nazi Germany, the Soviet Union, and elsewhere alongside Americans’ efforts to circumvent foreign regulatory systems in the quest to expand markets and bring their ideas to new publics. Lemberg shows how in the decades following the Second World War American free-flow policies reshaped the world’s information landscape, though not always as intended. Through burgeoning information diplomacy and development aid, Washington diffused new media ranging from television and satellite broadcasting to global English. But these actions also spurred overseas actors to articulate alternative understandings of information freedom and of how information flows might be regulated. Bridging the historiographies of the United States in the world, human rights, decolonization and development, and media and technology, Barriers Down excavates the analog roots of digital-age debates over the politics and ethics of transnational information flows.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCommunication, International. 0aMass media and culturezUnited States. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aMass mediazUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Media & Communications.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics 2019z9783110606065oZDB-23-DBV08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013040uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/lemb1821640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544030423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/978023154